=E2=80=99s not a big deal for everyone else, I think we=E2=80=99re just rea=
lly early, in hindsight. And this whole idea of large companies and nation =
states having to have an answer to GPT-3 or 4, and having to have clusters =
of tens of thousands of GPUs will happen. I just think it=E2=80=99ll take a=
 really long time. And I actually think ChatGPT was very significant in tha=
t regard. But to us, in Silicon Valley, it was actually not a big event.

Its main significance was, as I think about this Christmas, we=E2=80=99re r=
ecording this before Christmas, this is going to be one of those things whe=
re American families are going to be sitting at the table and discussing AI=
 and having conversations about what is human creativity really? And people=
 are developing opinions, that=E2=80=99s happening. So if you give that a c=
ouple of months, I think you=E2=80=99re going to end up seeing, at some poi=
nt, regulators, conversations, it=E2=80=99s going to get on C-SPAN.

So I think the GPU paradox sort of will be solved. I always think of one of=
 the worst things one could do is be a trader in the public market sort of =
using West Coast mindsets, because in your West Coast head, everything happ=
ens extremely quickly. You=E2=80=99re very early to things.

*Diffusion, no pun intended, takes a long time.*

*NF:* I think it=E2=80=99s that too. Hardware demand comes from inference, =
not from training. Inference is going to dominate. Inference comes from pro=
ducts that have wide usage, and we just don=E2=80=99t have very many produc=
ts with wide usage yet. We do have some that have grown a lot and you saw L=
ensa ran out of GPUs, at least at some point.

*Honestly, I think Lensa is on the level of ChatGPT for importance. And not=
 because Lensa=E2=80=99s going to be a big company in the long run.*

*NF:* Agreed.

*But what it signifies about what products that leverage AI actually look l=
ike, and how quickly demand can ramp.*

*NF:* And I do think around the dinner table at Christmas, the phone gets p=
assed around, =E2=80=9Ccheck this out. Check out ChatGPT. Check out Lensa.=
=E2=80=9D

*And everyone=E2=80=99s going to want these images immediately. I honestly =
think Nvidia=E2=80=99s in a really hard spot, because they obviously dramat=
ically over forecasted for the previous generation, and they=E2=80=99ve jus=
t gotten destroyed financially. And I do wonder if they over-corrected. And=
 Lensa is kind of my example for why. No one saw this coming because no one=
 saw Stable Diffusion coming, and to just explode like that and to utterly =
and completely hit the wall as far as GPU availability goes, I don=E2=80=99=
t think that=E2=80=99s a one-off. I see that as being the first of many exp=
losive uses like this.*

*DG:* Yeah, I think that=E2=80=99s right. And I think that use case was a r=
elatively small model. I think things will get much more complicated from s=
ome of these larger models.

*Well, I mean, the question too is if it ends up running locally then that =
doesn=E2=80=99t help Nvidia very much.*

*DG:* Right. Nvidia=E2=80=99s hope is that the really valuable stuff requir=
es running inference on eight GPUs. That=E2=80=99s their hope.**

*Yeah, we=E2=80=99re back to the local question I mean Apple is so well pla=
ce. All this stuff is downstream to Stable Diffusion. That probably is I th=
ink is the most important moment of 2022 when we look backwards, because al=
l this sort of stuff is so downstream from that. That lends itself to produ=
ct exploration. The other thing is that OpenAI costs money, so it literally=
 costs money to experiment, and Stable Diffusion does not. And when you sca=
le that across all the potential explorers and hackers and tinkerers in the=
 world, it=E2=80=99s a massive difference. And then you add on the potentia=
l to run locally, the potential to expand it to other places. That=E2=80=99=
s the breakthrough. And it may be even a bigger one if my on-the-spot idea =
that vision actually might be more important than text, contra to all our e=
xpectations, is true.*

*DG:* It=E2=80=99s a big area of debate. It=E2=80=99s good you have an opin=
ion.

*Well, happy to change it, if necessary. It=E2=80=99s good to talk to you g=
uys. Merry Christmas, Happy Hanukkah, Happy Holidays, Happy New Year. What =
a year. The great thing is it=E2=80=99s really exciting. At the end of last=
 year, personally, I was kind of feeling like, =E2=80=9CMan, I just don=E2=
=80=99t know if I want to keep doing this, what is in the future other than=
 regulation and antitrust?=E2=80=9D which I was just sick of. And this is s=
omething completely new and it=E2=80=99s really exciting. And maybe there=
=E2=80=99s confirmation bias, because I want there to be new and exciting, =
but this does feel very real.*

*DG:* Yeah, I think that=E2=80=99s right. The healthy vibrancy Silicon Vall=
ey has right now I don=E2=80=99t think has been felt since the iPhone gold =
rush days. And so it feels good.

*NF:* And I have nothing against people who are into Web3, but one of the t=
hings that was sad about the Web3 era for me was that the demos weren=E2=80=
=99t very exciting. Someone would tell you about their Web3 idea, and you w=
ere never that impressed by the screenshot or the demo. It seemed to do som=
ething that you already know how to do but in a different way.

The demos are unbelievable in AI. It is like the iPhone app from, I don=E2=
=80=99t know, 2009 that you kind of passed around, =E2=80=9CLook at this.=
=E2=80=9D And I think there=E2=80=99s something maybe sort of deep about th=
at. You want that wow moment, want that magic moment from technology where =
you didn=E2=80=99t know that was possible, and now you can do it in your ha=
nd.

*If a picture=E2=80=99s worth a 1,000 words, a demo is worth a million doll=
ars.*

*NF:* Exactly.

*All right. Nat, Daniel, thanks for coming on again, and look forward to se=
eing what 2023 brings.*

*DG:* Same here. Thank you.

